		<published>2012-01-31T19:07:09+00:00</published>
		<id>https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=48410#p48410</id>
		<link href="https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=48410#p48410"/>
		<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: love-loader: load resources in a separate thread, easily]]></title>

		
		<content type="html" xml:base="https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?p=48410#p48410"><![CDATA[
<blockquote class="uncited"><div>Is that really a blocking call that benefits from loading in another thread?</div></blockquote>Not really. I mean it blocks, but it really only allocates some memory, and therefore takes barely any time.<br><br>As for the send/receive =&gt; set/get change, in the code I've written that's supposed to be portable I define local functions that either call send or set depending on the love version, and then use that. (Same goes for receive and get, of course.)<br><div class="codebox"><p>Code: </p><pre><code>local setlocal getif love._version_major &gt; 0 or love._version_minor &gt; 7 then    set = function(thread, key, value)        return thread:set(key, value)    end    get = function(thread, key)        return thread:get(key)    endelse    set = function(thread, key, value)        return thread:send(key, value)    end    get = function(thread, key)        return thread:receive(key)    endend</code></pre></div>(Untested, I may have borked the version check.)<br><br>EDIT: Something I thought of while looking at the code, perhaps you could implement a function that waits for the thread to finish, if it is not? It's something I've implemented in the past, where if someone was to skip the intro, it would just start loading all (remaining) resources in a blocking way.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="https://love2d.org/forums/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=147">bartbes</a> — Tue Jan 31, 2012 7:07 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
